Why It’s Failing Now With Named Users
When all users previously logged in as the same shared account:

The FMS app was configured once (registry, environment, file paths).

It ran in a known user profile context, often with relaxed or hardcoded paths like:

makefile
Copy
Edit
C:\Users\TunnelOps\AppData\...
C:\FlexCache\FMSProxy\dll\...
Now that users are logging in with individual accounts:

Each session runs under a different profile path, like:

makefile
Copy
Edit
C:\Users\edward.ball\AppData\
Environment variables such as FMS_HOME, FMS_WINDOWS_MULTIUSER may:

Not be inherited

Not be configured globally

Per-user .dll access or app config might be missing

 What This Means Technically
The FMS app:

Was likely configured once under the generic profile

Relied on that environment and file structure

Now fails under new users because the env vars or app paths aren't global/system-level

 Resolution Plan
1. Check if FMS_HOME and FMS_WINDOWS_MULTIUSER are defined system-wide
Run this as admin:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-ChildItem Env: | Where-Object { $_.Name -like "*FMS*" }
If they only show up under specific users — that's the issue.

2. Fix It: Set Environment Vars System-Wide
powershell
Copy
Edit
[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable("FMS_WINDOWS_MULTIUSER", "1", "Machine")
[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable("FMS_HOME", "C:\Path\To\FMS", "Machine")
3. Confirm .DLL Path
Make sure required .dll files in:

makefile
Copy
